pipes in c

pipes are one wya normally, when they are unnamed 

to make named pipe, use mkfifo() method



now more functions:

msgget() [message get] - used to create and access queue
msgsnd() [msg send]    - send a message to queue
msgrcv() [msg receive] - receive a message from queue
msgctl() [msg control] - to control or delete queue



1. msgget()

int msgget(key_t key, int msgflg) - key and flag as arguments. 
	key for identification, 
	flag for permissions.

example
int msgid=msgget(1234, 0666 | IPC_CREAT);
if(msgid==-1){
	perror(\"msgget failed\");
	exit(0);
}



2. msgsnd() and msgrcv()

Before using these, define a message structure:

struct msgbuf {
  long mtype; // message type (must be > 0)
  char mtext[100]; // message data
};

msgsnd()
int msgsnd(int msgid, const void *msgp, size_t msgsz, int msgflg);

msgid → message queue ID (returned by msgget)
msgp → pointer to message structure
msgsz → size of message (excluding mtype)
msgflg → control flag (0 for default)

Example:

struct msgbuf message;
message.mtype = 1;
strcpy(message.mtext, "Hello");

if(msgsnd(msgid, &message, sizeof(message.mtext), 0) == -1){
  perror("msgsnd failed");
}

msgrcv()

int msgrcv(int msgid, void *msgp, size_t msgsz, long msgtyp, int msgflg);

msgid → message queue ID
msgp → pointer to structure to store received message
msgsz → size of message (excluding mtype)
msgtyp → type of message to receive
msgflg → control flag

Example:

if(msgrcv(msgid, &message, sizeof(message.mtext), 1, 0) == -1){
  perror("msgrcv failed");
}



3. msgctl()

int msgctl(int msgid, int cmd, struct msqid_ds *buf);

msgid → message queue ID
cmd → control command
buf → pointer to msqid_ds structure (used for getting/setting info)

Common commands:

IPC_STAT → get queue information
IPC_SET → set queue information
IPC_RMID → remove (delete) message queue

Example (delete queue):

if(msgctl(msgid, IPC_RMID, NULL) == -1){
  perror("msgctl failed");
}







Shared Memory Functions

shmget() – create shared memory
shmat() – attach shared memory to process address space
shmdt() – detach shared memory
shmctl() – control or delete shared memory

shmget()

int shmget(key_t key, size_t size, int shmflg);

key → unique identifier
size → size of shared memory segment in bytes
shmflg → permissions and control flags

Example:

int shmid = shmget(1234, 1024, 0666 | IPC_CREAT);
if(shmid == -1){
  perror("shmget failed");
  exit(0);
}

shmat()

void *shmat(int shmid, const void *shmaddr, int shmflg);

shmid → shared memory ID
shmaddr → address to attach (NULL lets system choose)
shmflg → flag (0 for default)

Example:

char data = (char) shmat(shmid, NULL, 0);
if(data == (char*) -1){
  perror("shmat failed");
}

shmdt()

int shmdt(const void *shmaddr);

shmaddr → address returned by shmat

Example:

if(shmdt(data) == -1){
  perror("shmdt failed");
}

shmctl()

int shmctl(int shmid, int cmd, struct shmid_ds *buf);

shmid → shared memory ID
cmd → control command (IPC_RMID to delete)
buf → buffer (usually NULL when deleting)

Example:

shmctl(shmid, IPC_RMID, NULL);
